label: Solomonic race
properties: {'authority_id': 'p05hrsf', 'source': 'p05hrsf', 'spatial_coverage_description': 'Abyssinia', 'editorial_note': 'This row is somewhat cryptic; it falls on the same line as the "Ethiopian" components that seem to have referred to the Nubian kingdom in previous periods, but its two temporal moments are "the end of the Solomonic race" in ca. 960 and "restored Abyssinians" in ca. 1300. These two dates strongly suggest that here Priestley is referring to the Axumite kingdom and its uncertain predecessors for the first part of this row (960 is the date at which the Axumite dynasty is supposed to have been overthrown), and to the Solomonic Dynasty of Ethiopia in the second part (the intervening dynasty was overthrown in 1270).', 'spatial_coverage_uris': ['http://www.wikidata.org/entity/Q115']}

label: Roman antiquity (Roman Noricum)
properties: {'authority_id': 'p0s84tq', 'source': 'p0s84tq', 'spatial_coverage_description': 'Noricum', 'editorial_note': 'The period subsumes from the overarching periods defined for Roman Noricum ("Early Period," "Imperial Period," and "Late Antiquity"; derived from Hagmann 2021, <http://n2t.net/ark:/99152/p0s84tq>). Furthermore, this overarching period takes into account the early pre-occupation activities in the area of the urban settlement at the Magdalensberg ("Stadt auf dem Magdalensberg", Carinthia/AUT), the beginning of which is put around 50 BC (cf., Gassner et al. 2002–2003, 70. 369). Finally, in addition to the absolute early period, the highly late period between 488 and 500 AD is also considered, in the context of which, according to "classical" doctrine and in view of the written tradition (vita Sancti Severini), 488 AD a settlement of the remaining Roman population (so-called "Romanen" in German-speaking research) should have already taken place and which represents a historically highly ambiguous period during the transition to the early Middle Ages (cf., Eichert - Richards 2022, <http://n2t.net/ark:/99152/p0cwwzn>).', 'spatial_coverage_uris': ['http://www.wikidata.org/entity/Q40', 'http://www.wikidata.org/entity/Q215', 'http://www.wikidata.org/entity/Q183', 'http://www.wikidata.org/entity/Q38']}

label: Âge du Fer
properties:
{'authority_id': 'p09hq4n', 'source': 'p09hq4n', 'spatial_coverage_description': 'Parts of central continental western Europe', 'editorial_note': "This period is used by the ArkeoGIS and ArkeOpen projects, in the framework of a general chronology from the Paleolithic to the present day, of a central-western part of continental Europe. It is based on the periodization set up by INRAP and PACTOLS.
The territory covered by this chronology extends from the eastern part of France in the west to Moldavia in the east, and from the south of the UK through southern Germany to Slovenia and central France on a north/south axis.

Cette période est utilisée par les projets ArkeoGIS et ArkeOpen, dans le cadre d'une chronologie générale du Paléolithique à nos jours, d'une partie centrale-occidentale de l'Europe continentale. Elle se fonde sur la périodisation mise en place par l'INRAP et PACTOLS.

label: Rois étrusques
properties:
{'authority_id': 'p09hq4n', 'source': 'p09hq4n', 'spatial_coverage_description': 'Latium', 'editorial_note': "This period is used by the ArkeoGIS and ArkeOpen projects, in the framework of a chronology presenting the institutions and their representatives in the Roman-Byzantine world. From the year of the foundation of Rome by Romulus (the Ab Urbe Condita was defined by the monk Denys the Lesser). Until the fall of Constantinople and the death of Constantin XI Palaeologus, Dragases.

The 3 successive regimes - Monarchy, Republic and Empire - are presented in different periods. These periods are themed according to different criteria: the origin and family of the reigning ruler, the development of the law and changes to the institutions of the regime in place. This chronology is not exhaustive. The annual mandates of the consuls, reigns of less than a year or in chaotic succession are not presented. This chronology is numerical. For technical reasons, some end dates differ from historical dates to give priority to the start date of the following period. The historical dates are indicated in the period descriptions.

The information assembled and presented is taken from the following open sources: Adalberto GIOVANNINI, Heidelberger Akademie der Wissenschaften, Library of Congress, Ministère de l'éducation nationale, Wikipedia.

---

Cette période est utilisée par les projets ArkeoGIS et ArkeOpen, dans le cadre d'une chronologie qui présente les institutions et leurs représentants dans le monde romain-byzantin. À partir de l'année de la fondation de Rome par Romulus (l'Ab Urbe Condita a été définie par le moine Denys le Petit). Jusqu'au jour de la chute de Constantinople et à la mort de Constantin XI Paléologue, Dragasès.

Les 3 régimes successifs la Monarchie, la République, puis l'Empire sont présentés en différentes périodes.
Ces périodes sont thématiques suivant les différents critères que sont l'origine et la famille du régnant, l’évolution du droit et la modification des institutions du régime en place.
Cette chronologie n'est pas exhaustive. Les mandats annuels des consuls, les règnes de moins d'un an ou dans une succession chaotique ne sont pas présentés.
Cette chronologie est numérique. Pour des raisons techniques, certaines dates de fin son différentes des dates historiques pour donner la priorité de la date à la date de début de la période suivante. Les dates historiques sont indiquées dans les descriptions des périodes.

Les informations assemblées et présentées sont issues des sources ouvertes suivantes : Adalberto GIOVANNINI, Heidelberger Akademie der Wissenschaften, Library of Congress, Ministère de l'éducation nationale, Wikipedia.", 'spatial_coverage_uris': ['http://www.wikidata.org/entity/Q1048669']}
